commText: Fraser-McGurk and Abishek Porel are at the crease. Fraser-McGurk is on strike. Arshad Khan will open the attack
Arshad Khan to Fraser-McGurk, wide, swing but the line is wrong, starts down leg and swings further down, no chance for Fraser-McGurk
Arshad Khan to Fraser-McGurk, wide, once more Arshad sprays it down leg and gives no chance for Fraser-McGurk to make any sort of contact

Arshad Khan to Fraser-McGurk, no run, uhhh! How did that miss the off-stump? Fraser-McGurk clears his front leg and swings across the line, the good length ball swings back in and flies over off-stump. Just missed by a whisker
Arshad Khan to Fraser-McGurk, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Arshad Khan to Fraser-McGurk, out Caught by Naveen-ul-Haq!! What a start! Fraser-McGurk is out of here. He's gone for a duck and the smile on Rahul's face says it all. This was a back of a length delivery and swings in a bit, Fraser-McGurk looks to heave it over the leg-side and gets it high on the bat, the ball goes straight up and Naveen settles under it near long-on. Huge strike for Lucknow. Fraser-McGurk c Naveen-ul-Haq b Arshad Khan 0(2)
Shai Hope, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Arshad Khan to Shai Hope, 2 runs, inswinger around the hips, Hope tucks it backward of square leg and races back for the second
Delhi review! It is for a wide that is not given. Hope knew there was no contact and hence sent it upstairs. Nothing on UltraEdge. It is a wide..
Arshad Khan to Shai Hope, wide, full and swinging down leg, Hope attempts the flick and is nowhere close to connecting. The ball did not brush the pad or anything on the way to de Kock
Arshad Khan to Shai Hope, 1 run, full pitcher on off, Hope drives it hard into the ground and Arshad parries it wide of mid-off
FYI, Rahul is not keeping wickets, de Kock is
Arshad Khan to Abishek Porel, no run, on a length and outside off, Porel opens the bat face and punches to backward point
Arshad Khan to Abishek Porel, no run, fuller and swinging away, Porel is drawn into the drive and is beaten on the outside edge
Mohsin Khan, left-arm fast medium, comes into the attack
Mohsin Khan to Shai Hope, no run, I0$ back of a length on off, Hope knocks it back to Mohsin
There's a slip in place
Mohsin Khan to Shai Hope, no run, I0$ leg-lined delivery and Hope misses the flick, the ball deflects off the pad to mid-wicket
Mohsin Khan to Shai Hope, 1 run, I0$ fuller and angled across, Hope slices the drive off the outer half to third man

Mohsin Khan to Abishek Porel, SIX, short and width on offer, Porel does not bother to keep the cut down, he gets under it and upper cuts it behind square on the off-side, sending the ball sailing comfortably over the rope
Mohsin Khan to Abishek Porel, 1 run, I0$ short of length delivery with some extra bounce, Porel gets on top of the ball and steers it to third man
Mohsin Khan to Shai Hope, no run, I0$ full and at the stumps, Hope pushes it back to Mohsin

Arshad Khan to Abishek Porel, FOUR, angled in from back of a length, Porel is a bit cramped for room but manages to chip it over mid-wicket, the ball lands safely and bounces over the rope before Krunal can get there
Arshad Khan to Abishek Porel, FOUR, smashed! Porel puts on his skates, gives himself some room and nails the drive through the cover region

Arshad Khan to Abishek Porel, SIX, this is smart batting. Porel knew Arshad would shorten the length after being driven, so he waits on the back foot for the short of length delivery and pumps the pull into the deep mid-wicket stand. Pressure on Arshad now.. Rahul having a word with him
Arshad Khan to Abishek Porel, wide, the riposte from Arshad is a bouncer but too short and too high, Porel ducks and evades it comfortably. It is called a wide for height
Arshad Khan to Abishek Porel, 1 run, I0$ full pitcher around off, Porel pushes it to mid-off and quickly crosses over
Arshad Khan to Shai Hope, 1 run, I0$ good length ball on off, Hope eases it down the ground and Rahul tidies up from mid-off

Arshad Khan to Abishek Porel, FOUR, 21 from the over. Delhi needed that to get themselves going. Overpitched outside off, Porel leans forward and creams the drive through extra cover. No one bothered to chase that down
Yudhvir Singh Charak, right-arm fast medium, comes into the attack
Yudhvir Singh to Shai Hope, no run, short of length outside off, Hope slashes hard and fails to connect. He went too hard and lost his shape
Yudhvir Singh to Shai Hope, no run, I0$ short of length around off, Hope punches it straight to cover-point

Yudhvir Singh to Shai Hope, FOUR, Hope needs to step up as well and this boundary might just open him up. Back of a length delivery and not there for the drive, but the pitch is so good that Hope struck it on the rise and in the air over the extra cover region

Yudhvir Singh to Shai Hope, FOUR, that's even better. Short of length delivery and Hope drives it off the back foot, his weight was on the back leg and he thumps it over the wide mid-off area, one bounce and over the ropes
Yudhvir Singh to Shai Hope, SIX, back of a length delivery but Hope had the space to open his arms, he drags the heave over wide long-on and has no problem clearing the rope, 78-meter maximum

Yudhvir Singh to Shai Hope, 2 runs, 16 from this over. Slower ball and the ball does not come on, Hope is early into the pull and toe-ends it backward of square leg, scampers back easily for the second
Mohsin Khan [1.0-0-8-0] is back into the attack
Mohsin Khan to Abishek Porel, 1 run, I0$ off-pace delivery and Porel has to check his drive, pushes it to mid-off and quickly crosses over
Mohsin Khan to Shai Hope, FOUR, streaky! I0$ slower ball outside off, Hope throws his bat on the drive and thick outside edge flies over short third. Rahul does not mind that and applauds Mohsin
Mohsin Khan to Shai Hope, no run, I0$ short and bowled into the wicket, Hope is early into the pull and misses it by a long way
Mohsin Khan to Shai Hope, no run, backs away and Mohsin digs the slower ball into the pitch, I0$ and once again Hope misses the pull

Mohsin Khan to Shai Hope, no run, Rahul wanted to know if he could review for a caught behind. But got nothing from Mohsin or de Kock. He felt the ball clipped the glove and ballooned to de Kock. Slower bouncer, Hope is through the pull and the ball arrives later, brushes the helmet on the way to de Kock. Good they didn't review

Mohsin Khan to Shai Hope, no run, that's four dots in a row. And it is the same type of delivery - slow and short of length bowled into the pitch, Hope does not spot the change of pace and is early into the pull, no contact made
Naveen-ul-Haq, right-arm fast medium, comes into the attack

Naveen-ul-Haq to Abishek Porel, SIX, poor start from Naveen-ul-Haq. Short and down leg, so far down that Porel swivels to play the pull and has to really reach for it, the bottom hand comes off the bat handle but the ball still sails over fine leg
Naveen-ul-Haq to Abishek Porel, wide, slower ball down leg, Porel gets inside the line and misses the glance, wide called
Naveen-ul-Haq to Abishek Porel, no run, I0$ off-pace short delivery and Porel takes it on, but is through the ball and the ball flies past him
Naveen-ul-Haq to Abishek Porel, no run, Lucknow have resorted to slower short of length deliveries, Porel pulls and misses, the ball strikes him on the arm and rolls towards point. That would hurt
The physio has come out to check on Porel. He was struck on the right arm.

Naveen-ul-Haq to Abishek Porel, SIX, pace on and it ends up on the second tier. Short ball around leg-stump, Porel swivels as he takes it on and gets a big top-edge on the pull shot, the ball flies over fine leg and ends up into the crowd
Naveen-ul-Haq to Abishek Porel, no run, goes back to the slower ball, I0$ and Porel goes hard on the whip, gets an inside edge onto the pad

Naveen-ul-Haq to Abishek Porel, FOUR, ends the over with a poor delivery. Full toss on leg-stump, Porel swings hard and gets a thick inside edge, the ball rolls behind square on the leg-side and races to the boundary

Over Summary(1-6): *Fraser-McGurk is out for a duck as Arshad Khan traps him. *Porel hits the first sixer off Mohsin *Porel takes 21 off the third over *Yudhvir goes for 16 in his first over *Mohsin bowls a tight over *Naveen starts his spell by conceding a sixer

Timeout! This is a good start for Delhi Capitals after losing Fraser-McGurk for nought. They have raced to 73 even though Lucknow have found a way to bowl on this surface. The slower short of length deliveries are gripping and that will be the way to go for the bowlers. 250 might be too much on this pitch and anything around 200-220 would be quite competitive.

Sourav Ganguly: [on the season so far] It's been a bit up and down to be honest. We have played well, we didn't play well at the start and we came back and played well. The Bangalore game was a crucial game for us, we did not get the runs, we missed Rishabh Pant in that game. In IPL good Indian players are so important, but then that's the way the sport is. [on JFM] He has brought a lot on the table, I'm happily surprised with the way he has batted. I think this is his first time in the sub-continent, we have played on good wickets at Feroze Shah Kotla, but you still have to put them away. The attitude has been good which is very important for me, he works hard in the nets, doesn't miss training, he is there everyday, even on optional practice he comes. I see very good things for him in this format. Davey is a legend, unfortunately he got injured for a long period time, he missed almost 1 month of the season because of a hand injury. With Ricky around he guided Jake very well. What I like about him is he's hungry, he wants to play well. I know he missed out on the World Cup, Australia should have probably picked him, but that's the way it goes when you have so many good players in Warner, Travis Head and Mitch Marsh at 3, you will obviously miss out. But he's just 22 and he has got a long career and I'm sure he will be up and ready. For us, he is a gamechanger and that's what you need in this format. We will see how it goes. Keep it simple and win and then see where it goes.
Ravi Bishnoi, right-arm leg break, comes into the attack
Ravi Bishnoi to Shai Hope, 1 run, very full delivery outside off, Hope squeezes the drive to deep backward point
Teams losing most wickets in the Powerplay in IPL 2024 28 - DC 25 - MI 20 - RCB 20 - PBKS 20 - LSG

Highest powerplay scores for DC 92/0 vs MI, Delhi, 2024 88/2 vs SRH, Delhi, 2024 81/0 vs PBKS, Brabourne, 2022 78/2 vs RR, Delhi, 2024 73/1 vs LSG, Delhi, 2024 71/0 vs RCB, Bengaluru, 2008 DC have scored 70 or more in the powerplay eight times across the 17 editions, four of which have come in 2024 alone.
Ravi Bishnoi to Abishek Porel, 1 run, googly around off, Porel is squared up and squirts it off the outer half to backward point, Pooran fumbles and concedes the single
Ravi Bishnoi to Shai Hope, 2 runs, dragged short and Hope cracks it in front of square, Krunal gives chase and keeps it down to a brace
Ravi Bishnoi to Shai Hope, 1 run, flighted outside off, Hope drives it flat and uppishly to long-off, goes on the bounce
Stumping check sent upstairs. de Kock was not confident and just inquired with the square leg umpire. The back leg was dragged out but Porel gets back in before de Kock lights up the stumps. Not Out

Ravi Bishnoi to Abishek Porel, no run, wrong 'un outside off, Porel does not pick it and looks to drive, the ball spins away and beats the outside edge, he was reaching for the drive and hence was dragged out but quickly gets back in
Ravi Bishnoi to Abishek Porel, 1 run, flatter and short of length, Porel knocks it to long-on
Krunal Pandya, Left arm orthodox, comes into the attack

Krunal Pandya to Abishek Porel, FOUR, Krunal greeted with a superb cut shot. Short and drifted across off, Porel plays it late and that allows him to place it behind square between the two fielders inside the ring

Krunal Pandya to Abishek Porel, 1 run, fifty for Porel. Second of the season. He has stepped up in the failure of Fraser-McGurk, gets there off just 21 balls. Raises his bat and acknowledges the applause of his team mates. Flatter delivery and Porel tucks it to mid-wicket
Another stumping check which de Kock is not too fussed about. The players are not even gathering. They are all on their place ready for the next ball. The back leg is firmly grounded. Not Out..
Krunal Pandya to Shai Hope, wide, darted down leg, Hope misses the glance and de Kock is quick to remove the bails, but the back leg never left the crease
Krunal Pandya to Shai Hope, 2 runs, sliding in with the angle, Hope nudges it into the mid-wicket pocket and races back for the second
Krunal Pandya to Shai Hope, no run, quicker and drifting in, Hope gets an inside edge on the flick and the ball goes quickly to short fine
Krunal Pandya to Shai Hope, 1 run, quicker and skidding in, Hope squirts an inside edge to deep square leg and settles with a single
Krunal Pandya to Abishek Porel, no run, flatter and pushed through, Porel knocks it to the left of Krunal

Ravi Bishnoi to Shai Hope, SIX, thumped! This hardly took over. Fired full around off, Hope clears his front leg and smokes it over Porel, not much elevation behind the shot but it goes crashing into the ad boards
Ravi Bishnoi to Shai Hope, no run, googly on short of length, Hope looks to pull and is hit on the body
Ravi Bishnoi to Shai Hope, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Ravi Bishnoi to Shai Hope, out Caught by Rahul!! Taken on the second attempt by Rahul. The partnership is broken and Hope is gone. Flatter and outside off, Hope had the space to open his arms and he slaps it straight to cover, struck it hard and around chest height, Rahul had to take it in an awkward position and the ball popped out, lobbed to his right and he moved quickly, dived and took it with both hands before the ball hit the ground. Shai Hope c Rahul b Ravi Bishnoi 38(27) [4s-3 6s-2]

Ravi Bishnoi to Abishek Porel, 1 run, darts it fuller and Porel drills it straight down the ground, the ball hits Pant on the pad and deflects to long-on

Naveen-ul-Haq to Abishek Porel, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Naveen-ul-Haq to Abishek Porel, out Caught by Pooran!! Excellent catch by Pooran. This looked to be sailing over but not when Pooran is patrolling the rope. Yudhvir Singh to Axar, no run, short outside off, Axar tries to ramp and misses, his feet were off the ground, the ball was over the head, but the third ump thinks that in a normal batting stance, the ball would have gone below the head. I'm not too sure, Yudhvir Singh is a tad lucky. The third ump feels the leg was bent and the ball would have been below the head in a normal stance. DC lose a review

Yudhvir Singh to Axar, 2 runs, dropped by Bishnoi at deep mid-wicket. Length delivery on the stumps, Axar skies the loft and Bishnoi drops it again, this was a simpler chance to the previous one, should have been taken. Wonder if he got fingertips even to that

Yudhvir Singh goes round the wicket.
Yudhvir Singh to Axar, 1 run, full around off, Axar slices the loft and it falls in front of the onrushing long-off
Yudhvir Singh to Tristan Stubbs, 2 runs, slower ball well outside off, Tristan Stubbs cuts and the bottom-edge goes wide of short third man, Tristan Stubbs scampers back for the 2nd. DC end on 208

21:24 Local Time, 15:54 GMT, 21:24 IST: DC cross 200. But LSG will feel they have a chance to win this. The pitch's a belter and the boundaries are short here. JFM went early but Porel and Hope put on a stand of 92 which stabilised the innings. The left-hander played beautifully again here and put away the loose stuff. Then Pant come on and struck a handy 33 before Tristan Stubbs finished with a 57 off just 25 balls. He took his time for the first 20 balls or so before exploding. Bishnoi through the middle overs kept it tight and bowled it flat and fast outside off, beating the batters on the cut a lot. A couple of catches dropped by Bishnoi for LSG who were average on the field. It's a must-win game for them, so they will be looking to chase this down. Back for the reply in 5 minutes...

Tristan Stubbs: It was quite tough when I walked in. I could not get myself on some intensity, but once I got going it started to flow. I always feel like I can give myself a bit of time and then catch up. You never know on this ground, but it is stopping a bit and hopefully it is enough. Just playing in front of so many people is incredible
